      Web of debt
   =20
 =20
The Financial Times has a fun graphic feature titled =E2=80=9CHow private e=
quity tangled banks in a web of debt,=E2=80=9D the essential point of which=
 is that everything in finance is more fun with a bit of leverage:=09If the=
re=E2=80=99s a company, a private equity fund can buy it, putting up some o=
f its own money (the equity) and borrowing the rest, secured by the assets =
of the company.=09The private credit fund that made the loan in Step 1 can =
put up some of its own money and borrow the rest from a bank to fund that l=
oan.=09The private equity fund buying the company in Step 1 can temporarily=
 borrow the money it uses to write the equity check (a =E2=80=9Csubscriptio=
n line=E2=80=9D), secured by the commitments of its investors (its limited =
partners) to eventually put up the money.=09After buying the company, the p=
rivate equity fund can take out a margin loan, secured by its equity stake =
in the company.=09Or it can take out a net asset value loan, secured by its=
 equity stakes in a whole portfolio of companies it owns.=09Also the compan=
y can borrow more money to pay dividends to the private equity fund.=09The =
limited partners can sell their stakes in the private equity fund to a seco=
ndaries fund, which can borrow some of the money to buy them.=09The general=
 partners (sponsors) of the private equity fund=C2=A0can borrow money,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Csecured by management fees and carried interest income.=E2=80=
=9D=09Or other funds can borrow money to buy the general partners=E2=80=99 =
stakes in their firms.=C2=A0=09I am sure I am missing some?I once wrote tha=
t =E2=80=9Ca (the?) main move in finance=E2=80=9D is this: You take a thing=
 with some risk, you divide it into a risky first-loss piece (the equity) a=
nd a safer second-loss piece (the debt), you sell the risky piece to people=
 who want high returns and the safe piece to people who want safety. =E2=80=
=9CAlso you can compose this move: You can divide a bunch of things into ju=
nior and senior claims, bundle a set of junior or senior claims together, a=
nd then slice that bundle into new junior and senior claims.=E2=80=9D This =
FT feature is a series of pictures illustrating that point. Take a set of c=
ash flows anywhere in the vicinity of private equity =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ear=
nings of a company, the returns to private equity limited partners, the com=
mitments of those LPs, the fees paid to the general partners, the the payme=
nts on a loan =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you can slice it into safer and riskier pi=
eces, fund the safe piece with debt and juice the returns on the riskier pi=
ece.It would be weird if it were otherwise? Like, if you buy a house, you w=
ill probably take out a mortgage, funding most of your purchase with debt (=
funded by a bank/insurer/whoever who wants a safe return) and some of it wi=
th equity (funded by you, who want=C2=A0levered exposure to home-price appr=
eciation). And then you=E2=80=99ll go about your day without thinking =E2=
=80=9Chmm how could I slice this up further,=E2=80=9D because you are not f=
undamentally in the business of slicing up cash flows. But private equity f=
irms are, so every cash flow they come into contact with gets sliced up.The=
 point of all of this is that at the bottom you have some set of businesses=
 with some set of cash flows, and then those cash flows are sliced and reco=
mbined in various ways so that lots of different people (private equity GPs=
, their LPs, the GPs and LPs of secondaries and GP-stake and private-credit=
 funds, bank lenders, etc.) get exactly the package of cash flows they want=
. And that is the business they are all in.=E2=80=9CAs higher interest rate=
s put pressure on borrowers,=E2=80=9D says the FT,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cregulators=
 are asking an important question: could the private equity industry pose a=
 risk to the wider financial system?=E2=80=9D Sure? I guess? I am not parti=
cularly worried =E2=80=94=C2=A0the banks=E2=80=99=C2=A0claims on all of thi=
s stuff seem pretty senior, and the substrate at the bottom of all of this =
leverage (cash flows from lots of businesses) seems reasonably robust and d=
iversified. But=C2=A0a=C2=A0(the?) main risk to the financial system is whe=
n people put money into assets that they think are safe, and those safe ass=
ets turn out to be correlated and risky. The more sorts of safe tranches yo=
u manufacture out of the basic raw materials of business cash flows, the mo=
re ways some of them could go wrong.
