      Debanking
   =20
 =20
If you are a terrorist, and you=C2=A0have an account at a US bank, and the =
bank finds out that you are a terrorist, it will close your account. Banks =
are, among many other things, in the business of implementing US criminal a=
nd national security policies. If a bank catches you doing terrorism, or mo=
ney laundering, or sex trafficking, or exporting to Iran, or lots of other =
things the US government doesn=E2=80=99t like, it is supposed to stop you. =
If it fails to stop you, it will get in trouble.If the bank thinks with, li=
ke, 40% probability that you are a terrorist, or a sex trafficker, or Irani=
an, it will probably also close your account. Why take the risk? In 2020, D=
eutsche Bank AG paid a $150 million fine to New York banking authorities fo=
r letting Jeffrey Epstein have a checking account despite seeing =E2=80=9Cr=
ed flags=E2=80=9D about his sex crimes. If a bank sees =E2=80=9Cred flags=
=E2=80=9D that you=C2=A0might=C2=A0be up to something illegal or sanctioned=
, and=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0shut down your account, it could get in tro=
uble and pay big fines and be branded an accessory to=C2=A0crimes. The mone=
y the bank makes from your checking account is just not worth taking that r=
isk, especially if your account is a lot smaller than Epstein=E2=80=99s was=
. And that risk is all one way: It=E2=80=99s not like the bank is going to =
get fined $150 million for shutting down your account wrongly.This can be f=
rustrating, of course, if (1) you are=C2=A0not a terrorist but (2) somethin=
g in your profile suggests, to the bank=E2=80=99s inscrutable processes, th=
at you have like a 10% chance of being a terrorist.=C2=A0Meanwhile, if you =
are a Republican, and you have an account at a US bank, and the bank finds =
out that you are a Republican, will it close your account? Ha, no. But this=
 is apparently a worry, so the state of Florida passed a law making it ille=
gal for a bank to =E2=80=9Cdeny, or cancel, suspend, or terminate its servi=
ces to a person, or to otherwise discriminate against a person in making av=
ailable such services, or in the terms or conditions of such services, on t=
he basis of=E2=80=9D a long list of factors including:The person's politica=
l opinions, speech, or affiliations; =E2=80=A6Any factor if it is not a qua=
ntitative, impartial, and risk-based standard, including any such factor re=
lated to the person=E2=80=99s business sector; ...The person's engagement i=
n the exploration, production, utilization, transportation, sale, or manufa=
cture of fossil fuel-based energy, timber, mining, or agriculture.The perso=
n's support of the state or Federal Government in combating illegal immigra=
tion, drug trafficking, or human trafficking.Again, though, the point with =
Jeffrey Epstein is not that Deutsche Bank had a =E2=80=9Cquantitative, impa=
rtial, and risk-based standard=E2=80=9D for kicking out sex offenders, and =
failed to apply it to Epstein. The point is that Deutsche Bank saw subjecti=
ve =E2=80=9Cred flags=E2=80=9D about Epstein, and failed to kick him out fo=
r qualitative, partial (and risk-based) reasons. The point is that banks ar=
e expected to apply the rules in fuzzy ways. I wrote at the time:Financial =
regulation is universal regulation, and it is in a sense=C2=A0easier=C2=A0r=
egulation than the rest of the law. If police and prosecutors wanted to sto=
p Epstein, they would have had to arrest him and have a public trial in whi=
ch they proved to a jury that he was still doing crimes. Perhaps they would=
 also have faced political pressure from Epstein=E2=80=99s well-connected f=
riends. Given all of this, it took a long time for the authorities to work =
up the nerve to arrest him.If Deutsche Bank had wanted to stop processing p=
ayments for Epstein, they could have just sent him a letter saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe're closing your account=E2=80=9D with no explanation and no appeal.=
=C2=A0But in Florida, now, there=E2=80=99s an appeal.
  [2]
=C2=A0Now the risks for the bank are not one-way: If it=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99=
t=C2=A0kick you out, and you turn out to be a criminal, it can get in troub=
le for facilitating crime; if it=C2=A0does=C2=A0kick you out, and you turn =
out not to be a criminal, it can get in trouble for discrimination.Also I m=
ean if you read the law literally then if the bank says =E2=80=9Cthe proble=
m with this guy is that he is a member of the Iranian Revolutionary Guard,=
=E2=80=9D so it cancels your account, you can complain=C2=A0to Florida that=
 it is discriminating against you for your political affiliations?=C2=A0Her=
e=E2=80=99s a fun=C2=A0Wall Street Journal story:The U.S. Treasury Departme=
nt said state laws targeted at stopping banks from dropping customers over =
their politics could harm national security, singling out Florida legislati=
on recently signed by Gov. Ron DeSantis.Banks need to be able to probe cust=
omers so they can prevent money laundering and counter terrorist financing,=
 Treasury Undersecretary Brian Nelson said in a letter to lawmakers sent Th=
ursday.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CState laws interfering with financial institutions=E2=
=80=99 ability to comply with national security requirements heighten the r=
isk that international drug traffickers, transnational organized criminals,=
 terrorists and corrupt foreign officials will use the U.S. financial syste=
m to launder money, evade sanctions and threaten our national security,=E2=
=80=9D Nelson said. =E2=80=A6Florida=E2=80=99s law against looking into a c=
ustomer=E2=80=99s affiliations might, for example, stop a bank from conside=
ring their connection to a terrorist group, Treasury said.=C2=A0The law als=
o bars banks from considering factors =E2=80=9Crelated to the person=E2=80=
=99s business sector,=E2=80=9D which some banks might interpret as prohibit=
ing them from taking a close look at high-risk sectors that trade in goods =
Russia could use for its war effort and the sale of fentanyl precursors, th=
e Treasury Department said.I assume that if you are a bank and you think an=
 account might belong to=C2=A0an Iranian government official or a drug traf=
ficker, you will probably still be significantly more worried about the ris=
k of keeping the account open than you are about the risk of closing it and=
 getting a complaint. But now I guess there is a little bit of risk the oth=
er way.
