      Is pricing power illegal?
   =20
 =20
The traditional view is something like: In an open market with a lot of com=
peting firms, consumers will generally pay low prices, because if one firm =
charged high prices consumers would just switch to the other firms. =E2=80=
=9CPricing power,=E2=80=9D in this view, is virtually synonymous with =E2=
=80=9Cmonopoly power=E2=80=9D: The only way a firm could charge high prices=
 is if there are no viable competitors.If you were really good at price dis=
crimination, though, this might not be true. Like:=09You=C2=A0run a hardwar=
e store.=09There=E2=80=99s another, equally good hardware store down the bl=
ock.=09Price tags do not exist: If anyone wants to buy something from you, =
they ask you the price and you tell them.=09You are extremely good at readi=
ng people.=09If they ask you =E2=80=9Chow much does this hammer cost,=E2=80=
=9D and you can tell by looking at them that they are savvy about hammer pr=
ices and willing to walk a block to the other store, you will tell them a c=
ompetitive price.=09If they ask you =E2=80=9Chow much does this hammer cost=
,=E2=80=9D and you can tell by looking at them that they have plenty of mon=
ey, are insensitive to price and don=E2=80=99t know there=E2=80=99s another=
 hardware store nearby, you will smoothly say =E2=80=9Cthat hammer is $50=
=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99ll pay you.Is that an=C2=A0antitrust violation?=
=C2=A0I feel like the traditional answer is =E2=80=9Cno, of course not=E2=
=80=9D: You are not a monopolist, there=E2=80=99s another competitor nearby=
, you are just good at business. On the other hand, if the purpose of antit=
rust regulation is to keep consumer prices low, there=E2=80=99s something a=
 bit unsettling about this: You don=E2=80=99t have monopoly power, but you =
do have the power to charge supracompetitive prices, which is kind of the b=
ad thing people are worried about.Technology seems to be moving toward perf=
ect price discrimination, and the Wall Street Journal reports:The Federal T=
rade Commission is seeking information about how artificial intelligence an=
d other technological tools may allow companies to vary prices using data t=
hey collect about individual consumers=E2=80=99 finances and shopping habit=
s.The FTC said its study aims to reveal the inner workings of personalized =
pricing, a way of varying prices down to the individual level that has long=
 been the holy grail of marketing. The commission says the algorithms and m=
odels that drive pricing strategies are opaque and may rely on surveilling =
consumers=E2=80=99 online footprints.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAmericans deserve to kn=
ow whether businesses are using detailed consumer data to deploy surveillan=
ce pricing, and the FTC=E2=80=99s inquiry will shed light on this shadowy e=
cosystem of pricing middlemen,=E2=80=9D Chair Lina Khan said in a statement=
 announcing the review.The FTC is issuing civil subpoenas to financial comp=
anies and consultants that help companies decide pricing strategies: Master=
card, JPMorgan Chase, McKinsey, Accenture, Revionics, Bloomreach, TASK and =
PROS. Their clients tend to be in the retail, restaurant, grocery, travel, =
finance and hospitality industries, officials said.I suppose there is also =
a traditional antitrust element here: If all the companies subscribe to the=
 same pricing consultants, then arguably they are coordinating their prices=
 with each other.
