<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Web of debt</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Financial Times <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36172030.194392/aHR0cHM6Ly9pZy5mdC5j=
b20vcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHkv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd3b0587c" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">has a f=
un graphic feature</a> titled =E2=80=9CHow private equity tangled banks in =
a web of debt,=E2=80=9D the essential point of which is that everything in =
finance is more fun with a bit of leverage:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type=
: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">If there=E2=80=99s a company, a private equity fund can buy it, p=
utting up some of its own money (the equity) and borrowing the rest, secure=
d by the assets of the company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Th=
e private credit fund that made the loan in Step 1 can put up some of its o=
wn money and borrow the rest from a bank to fund that loan.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The private equity fund buying the company in Ste=
p 1 can temporarily borrow the money it uses to write the equity check (a =
=E2=80=9Csubscription line=E2=80=9D), secured by the commitments of its inv=
estors (its limited partners) to eventually put up the money.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">After buying the company, the private equity fu=
nd can take out a margin loan, secured by its equity stake in the company.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or it can take out a net asset val=
ue loan, secured by its equity stakes in a whole portfolio of companies it =
owns.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Also the company can borrow =
more money to pay dividends to the private equity fund.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">The limited partners can sell their stakes in the pri=
vate equity fund to a secondaries fund, which can borrow some of the money =
to buy them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The general partners =
(sponsors) of the private equity fund=C2=A0can borrow money,=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=
secured by management fees and carried interest income.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Or other funds can borrow money to buy the g=
eneral partners=E2=80=99 stakes in their firms.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">I am sure I am missing some?</li></ol><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3617=
2030.194392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjE=
tMTAtMDcvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1sb29raW5nLWZvci10ZXRoZXItcy1tb2=
5leT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI0MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4375e1a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">once wrote</a> that =E2=80=9Ca (the?=
) main move in finance=E2=80=9D is this: You take a thing with some risk, y=
ou divide it into a risky first-loss piece (the equity) and a safer second-=
loss piece (the debt), you sell the risky piece to people who want high ret=
urns and the safe piece to people who want safety. =E2=80=9CAlso you can co=
mpose this move: You can divide a bunch of things into junior and senior cl=
aims, bundle a set of junior or senior claims together, and then slice that=
 bundle into new junior and senior claims.=E2=80=9D This FT feature is a se=
ries of pictures illustrating that point. Take a set of cash flows anywhere=
 in the vicinity of private equity =E2=80=94=C2=A0the earnings of a company=
, the returns to private equity limited partners, the commitments of those =
LPs, the fees paid to the general partners, the the payments on a loan =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and you can slice it into safer and riskier pieces, fund the sa=
fe piece with debt and juice the returns on the riskier piece.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would be weird if it were otherwise? Like, if you b=
uy a house, you will probably take out a mortgage, funding most of your pur=
chase with debt (funded by a bank/<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/36172030.194392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMTYvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tY2FuLXR3ZWV0LWhpcy1uZXctZnVuZD=
9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzI0MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9b=
mV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MjQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB56dc36c6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">insurer</a>/whoever who wants a safe ret=
urn) and some of it with equity (funded by you, who want=C2=A0levered expos=
ure to home-price appreciation). And then you=E2=80=99ll go about your day =
without thinking =E2=80=9Chmm how could I slice this up further,=E2=80=9D b=
ecause you are not fundamentally in the business of slicing up cash flows. =
But private equity firms are, so every cash flow they come into contact wit=
h gets sliced up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of all of this =
is that at the bottom you have some set of businesses with some set of cash=
 flows, and then those cash flows are sliced and recombined in various ways=
 so that lots of different people (private equity GPs, their LPs, the GPs a=
nd LPs of secondaries and GP-stake and private-credit funds, bank lenders, =
etc.) get exactly the package of cash flows they want. And that is the busi=
ness they are all in.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAs higher in=
terest rates put pressure on borrowers,=E2=80=9D says the FT,=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cregulators are asking an important question: could the private equity in=
dustry pose a risk to the wider financial system?=E2=80=9D Sure? I guess? I=
 am not particularly worried =E2=80=94=C2=A0the <em>banks=E2=80=99=C2=A0</e=
m>claims on all of this stuff seem pretty senior, and the substrate at the =
bottom of all of this leverage (cash flows from lots of businesses) seems r=
easonably robust and diversified. But=C2=A0a=C2=A0(the?) main risk to the f=
inancial system is when people put money into assets that they think are sa=
fe, and those safe assets turn out to be correlated and risky. The more sor=
ts of safe tranches you manufacture out of the basic raw materials of busin=
ess cash flows, the more ways some of them could go wrong.</p><table class=
